Terminally ill comic looks to form a friendship with the guy who followed him on stage after he performed a rather dark routine.

Judd Apatow's latest film is more serious, more assured and more mature. Its a finely crafted film that shows Apatow's growth as a filmmaker. Its nice to see the very good performances from Adam Sandler and Seth Rogen (an actor I only occasionally like) Beyond the technical aspects and the fine performances this film fell flat for me. Its not something that wasn't expected, I have yet to like any film Apatow has directed, and I've only begrudgingly liked the one's he's written and produced. On some level the films all seem basically the same thing over and over again. Here I never really cared. The characters, despite solid performances never seemed like anyone that I would want to spend time with. For me it was like all of Apatow's other films something I viewed as an endurance test.

If you liked Apatow's earlier films you'll like this, if you didn't you won't
